</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C9886FFCFFFAB0380FDF9FCF54CA3" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF9CB0DFFCFFFAB0380FDF9FCF54CA3" blockId="44.[120,1227,524,1559]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
ETYMOLOGY: The genus name comes from the Latin 
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB003BFDF6FCB74C44" box="[787,875,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">magnus</emphasis>
, for “large,” and 
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB071AFDF9FB824C44" box="[1074,1118,599,625]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">lens</emphasis>
for “eye” in reference to the large protruding eyes. Gender: feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C9886FFCFFFAB0380FD0CFDB94DD2" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF9CB0DFFCFFFAB0380FD0CFDFA4DF7" blockId="44.[120,1227,524,1559]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
DIAGNOSIS: Body large, head with ocular sclerites each bearing eight pairs of large and bulging simple eyes (vs. seven small ones in 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0171FD69FD1D4CD4" authorityName="Beardsley" authorityYear="1969" box="[601,705,711,737]" class="Insecta" family="Putoidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Putoidae</taxonomicName>
, and six in 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0067FD69FC634CD4" authorityName="Koteja" authorityYear="2000" box="[847,959,711,737]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Solicoccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB0067FD69FC634CD4" box="[847,959,711,737]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Solicoccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, diagonally arranged); antenna filiform, almost trinodose (vs. not nodose in 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB01F5FD42FC914D33" authorityName="Koteja" authorityYear="2000" box="[733,845,748,774]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Solicoccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB01F5FD42FC914D33" box="[733,845,748,774]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Solicoccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), with long setae; forewings with microtrichia; legs slender, tibia with setae becoming spinelike on ventral surface distally; tarsus 2-segmented; claw with spinelike digitules; abdominal segment VIII with a pair of wax filaments, indicative of a pair of glandular pouches (vs. two pairs of glandular pouches in 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0707FCF2FB7C4D43" authorityName="Koteja" authorityYear="2000" box="[1071,1184,860,886]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Solicoccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB0707FCF2FB7C4D43" box="[1071,1184,860,886]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Solicoccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on abdominal segments VII and VIII). Penial sheath large triangular, with a narrow pointed aedeagus (vs. long and bifurcated in 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0287FC09FDC64DF7" authorityName="Beardsley" authorityYear="1969" box="[431,538,935,962]" class="Insecta" family="Putoidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Putoidae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9CB0DFFCFFFAB0380FC62FDB94DD2" blockId="44.[120,1227,524,1559]" box="[168,613,972,999]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
SPECIES INCLUDED: 
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB02A6FC63FDFC4DD3" box="[398,544,972,998]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB02A6FC63FDC14DD3" authority="Vea &amp; Grimaldi, 2015" authorityName="Vea &amp; Grimaldi" authorityYear="2015" box="[398,541,972,998]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera incertae sedis" genus="Magnilens" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glaesaria" status="n. sp.">M. glaesaria</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A201AA64FFCFFFAB0100FC63FDB94DD2" box="[552,613,973,999]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C9886FFCFFFAB0380FC5CFC1D4823" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF9CB0DFFCFFFAB0380FC5CFC1D4823" blockId="44.[120,1227,524,1559]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
COMMENTS: 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB021FFC5FFE744A3E" authorityName="Vea &amp; Grimaldi" authorityYear="2015" box="[311,424,1009,1035]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera incertae sedis" genus="Magnilens" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB021FFC5FFE744A3E" box="[311,424,1009,1035]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Magnilens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
definitely belongs to the taxa bearing a row of multiple simple eyes. This genus seems most similar to Recent 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0125FBB6FD9D4A04" box="[525,577,1048,1073]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Puto" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB0125FBB6FD9D4A04" box="[525,577,1048,1073]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Puto</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the following characters: the long antennal setae, the 2-segmented tarsus, with similar tibial spurs present ventrally and more numerous toward tarsus, presumable glandular pouches on abdominal segment VIII, each with two wax filaments, and the subtriangular, elongate penial sheath with a narrow aedeagus. However, significant differences also occur: the ocular sclerite bears very large and protruding eyes (vs. small round eyes in 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB071BFB03FBBB4AF3" box="[1075,1127,1197,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Puto" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB071BFB03FBBB4AF3" box="[1075,1127,1197,1222]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Puto</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), hamulohalteres bear two hamuli (vs. four hamuli), the tarsal digitules are undifferentiated (vs. differentiated), the claw denticles are absent (vs. present), the aedeagus is pointed apically (vs. bifurcated). The phylogenetic results based on morphological characters retrieved 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB00A7FAB2FBDD4B03" authorityName="Vea &amp; Grimaldi" authorityYear="2015" box="[911,1025,1308,1334]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera incertae sedis" genus="Magnilens" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB00A7FAB2FBDD4B03" box="[911,1025,1308,1334]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Magnilens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as sister genus to 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0350FAECFF394B69" authorityName="Koteja" authorityYear="2000" box="[120,229,1346,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Solicoccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB0350FAECFF394B69" box="[120,229,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Solicoccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB03DDFAECFE444B68" authorityName="Koteja" authorityYear="2000" box="[245,408,1346,1373]" class="Insecta" family="Labiococcidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Labiococcidae</taxonomicName>
) described in 
<collectingRegion id="498205EFFFCFFFAB011CFAECFD6D4B69" box="[564,689,1346,1372]" country="United States of America" name="New Jersey" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">New Jersey</collectingRegion>
amber (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD7B6FCFFCFFFAB0024FAECFC764B68" author="Koteja, J." box="[780,938,1346,1373]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="147 - 229" refId="ref37531" refString="Koteja, J. 2000 b. Scale insects (Homoptera, Coccinea) from Upper Cretaceous New Jersey amber. In D. A. Grimaldi (editor), Studies on fossils in amber, with particular reference to the Cretaceous of New Jersey: 147 - 229. Leiden: Backhuys Publishers." type="book chapter" year="2000">Koteja, 2000b</bibRefCitation>
) but not closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0350FAC9FF024BB4" authorityName="Beardsley" authorityYear="1969" box="[120,222,1383,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Putoidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Putoidae</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0273FAC9FE144BB4" authorityName="Koteja" authorityYear="2000" box="[347,456,1383,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Solicoccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB0273FAC9FE144BB4" box="[347,456,1383,1409]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Solicoccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB0177FAC9FD0D4BB4" authorityName="Vea &amp; Grimaldi" authorityYear="2015" box="[607,721,1383,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera incertae sedis" genus="Magnilens" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB0177FAC9FD0D4BB4" box="[607,721,1383,1409]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Magnilens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the small size and diagonal arrangement of simple eyes in the former, the presence of glandular pouches on abdominal segments VII and VIII (vs. only one segment [VIII] in 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB013DFA1CFD5A4BF9" authorityName="Vea &amp; Grimaldi" authorityYear="2015" box="[533,646,1458,1484]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera incertae sedis" genus="Magnilens" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB013DFA1CFD5A4BF9" box="[533,646,1458,1484]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Magnilens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and three hamuli on the hamulohaltere (vs. two). Unfortunately, the specimen orientation does not allow a comparison of the thoracic structures, and until more specimens are found, 
<taxonomicName id="4C46B08EFFCFFFAB02C4FA52FD824823" authorityName="Vea &amp; Grimaldi" authorityYear="2015" box="[492,606,1532,1558]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera incertae sedis" genus="Magnilens" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B932171FFFCFFFAB02C4FA52FD824823" box="[492,606,1532,1558]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Magnilens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered incertae familiae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
